'''Lindsay Margaret Errington''' is a Scottish [[art historian]] and former keeper for over 20 years at the [[National Gallery of Scotland]], Edinburgh, where she worked to establish a representative collection of [[Scottish art]].

==Early life==
Lindsay Errington was born in Edinburgh and trained as a painter at the [[Camberwell School of Art]] in London but did not follow that as a career. She studied art history at the [[Courtauld Institute of Art]] and later completed a PhD there<ref name=herald>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/11993794.Ambassador_for_Scotland_apos_s_art_heritage/ Ambassador for Scotland's art heritage.] ''The Herald'', originally published 2nd February 1989. Retrieved 2 July 2017.</ref> on the subject of "Social and religious themes in English Art" (1973). It was published in book form by Garland in 1984 in their [[Outstanding theses from the Courtauld Institute of Art]] series.

==Career==
Errington taught at the Newcastle College of Art but did not find the work to her liking, preferring to be in Scotland, and was appointed to a curatorial post at the National Gallery of Scotland in 1972, only the second woman to hold such a post. She was asked to look after the Scottish paintings, which her male colleagues did not think an honour, but which she was delighted to do.<ref name=herald/> She was at the gallery for over 20 years where she worked to establish a representative collection of [[Scottish art]]<ref name=herald/> and produced many of the monographs on Scottish artists in the Scottish Masters series.

In 1988-89 she was [[Slade Professor of Fine Art]] at the [[University of Cambridge]]<ref>[http://www.hoart.cam.ac.uk/aboutthedept/sladeprofs/sladeprofs/le456@cam.ac.uk Lindsay Errington.] Department of History of Art, University of Cambridge. Retrieved 2 July 2017.</ref> when she was the first Slade professor to lecture on Scottish art.<ref name=herald/>

In 2017, Errington published her most recent book, ''Private Views'', which featured images from the National Gallery's collection with verses composed in response to them.<ref>[http://www.arthistorynews.com/articles/4661_Art_and_poetry_ctd Art and poetry.] Art History News, 26 May 2017. Retrieved 2 July 2017.</ref>

